{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c6e031b4-30dd-4db6-ac5a-93b668163ef8","content":"In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are gone. The lifecycle is now managed on the **`Window`** class instead.\n\n**Direct equivalents:**\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI (Window) |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart` | `Created` |\n| `OnSleep` | `Stopped` |\n| `OnResume` | `Resumed` |\n\n**Option 1 — Override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to events:**\n\n```csharp\npublic partial class App : Application\n{\n    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    {\n        var window = new Window(new AppShell());\n\n        window.Created += (s, e) => { /* OnStart logic */ };\n        window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep logic */ };\n        window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* OnResume logic */ };\n\n        return window;\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Option 2 — Subclass `Window`:**\n\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated() { /* ... */ }\n    protected override void OnStopped() { /* ... */ }\n    protected override void OnResumed() { /* ... */ }\n}\n```\n\nThere are also `Activated`, `Deactivated`, and `Destroying` events for finer-grained control. For platform-specific hooks, use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8157f87b-1cc5-41f0-9755-abb452e79f21","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a straightforward knowledge question about the MAUI lifecycle API.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` in your `Application` class. In .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed. You now use the `Window` lifecycle events or the cross-platform lifecycle events through the `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`, or you can override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to window events.\n\nLet me give a concise answer:\n\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the `Application` class no longer has those lifecycle overrides. Instead, you override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and subscribe to `Window` events—`Created` maps to the old `OnStart`, while `Deactivated` and `Resumed` handle the sleep and resume scenarios respectively.","outputTokens":875,"requestId":"A84C:21155A:6C32CB:7C65BD:69FBE31A"},"id":"05510d25-aeef-4a70-aaf0-9d96b5c95d0f","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:56:10.697Z","parentId":"e968694a-9d29-428e-8edc-be5d9575270a"}
